defaultFunding beyond 2016default•
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHow should the BBC be funded beyond 2016? Is there a case for distributing funding for public service content more widely beyond the BBC? What comparisons can be made with the provision of public serv
defaultice content in other countries? 
default4.1 Pact is strong supporter of the BBC licence fee; this is essential for the delivery of quality broadcasting in the future and should be protected. The licence fee which is channelled
default into BBC programming also acts as seed funding driving the creation of British intellectual property. The licence fee gives the UK a competitive advantage and a platform into international markets, creating and sustaining thousands of jobs in the process.
default&#xa0;
default4.2 The BBC is the envy of public broadcasters around the world and a recent report
default underlines the value of the BBC in creating and selling Britain’
defaults 
default‘soft power’ overseas. The report demonstrated that cultural factors such as language, creativity and 
defaultvalues contribute to the UK’s attractiveness as a source of overseas trade and investment and that:
default•
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPeople who consume BBC services more frequently have more favourable perceptions of the UK
default•
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe more business leaders know and consume the BBC, the more like
defaultly they are to trade with the UK.
default&#xa0;
default4.3 The success of the current regime is demonstrated in the fact that TV exports have more than doubled over the last few years. The most recent Pact/UKTI Export report shows that UK TV exports continue to rise and were 
defaultup 4% overall to £1,178m in 2012. The main markets are the US and Europe but with strong growth in China 
default(+90%), Indonesia (+81%) and India (+42%) and future potential in other markets also.
default4.4 In terms of funding beyond 2016, Pact would support an approp
defaultriate annual increment to the licence fee. This may be in line with, or higher than, inflation taking into account the changing economic environment. Pact would be concerned that a failure to secure future funding for the BBC would erode the budget for fut
defaulture original content which is a driver of IP creation.
default&#xa0;
default4.5 Pact is opposed to any redistribution of the licence fee to other broadcasters. The BBC has integrated the licence fee into its business plan and operating model and demonstrated that it can creat
defaulte, deliver and sustain high quality content over a period of time. By redistributing this fee to other broadcasters, the current impact of the Public Service Broadcaster would be lost.
default&#xa0;
default4.6 Competition amongst the broadcasters is important to drive creativ
defaultity and innovation. By replacing the licence fee with advertising revenue in any way would damage the BBC’s unique service model. The BBC drives the world’s best TV industry which is vastly different from similar sized countries such as Italy with RaiUno. 
defaultThe competition angle is important in sustaining future success in the sector.
